In the convoluted realm of [particle physics](/Particle_physics), where existence itself is a matter of quantum probabilities, a **baryon** emerges as a distinct type of [composite particle](/Composite_particle). To put it in terms you might grasp, it's a [subatomic particle](/Subatomic_particle) that consistently houses an odd number of [valence quarks](/Valence_quark)—typically, three. This isn't a suggestion; it's a fundamental architectural principle. For instance, the very [protons](/Proton) and [neutrons](/Neutron) that constitute the mundane matter around you are quintessential examples of baryons. Since these particles are, by definition, constructed from [quarks](/Quark), they are naturally categorized within the broader [hadron](/Hadron) [family of particles](/List_of_particles). Furthermore, baryons possess half-integer [spin](/Spin_(physics)), a characteristic that firmly places them in the class of [fermions](/Fermion), obliging them to adhere to the stringent tenets of the [Pauli exclusion principle](/Pauli_exclusion_principle).

The term "baryon" itself, a rather fitting designation, was introduced by the discerning physicist [Abraham Pais](/Abraham_Pais) in 1953. Derived from the [Ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek) word "βαρύς" (barýs), meaning "heavy," this nomenclature was quite apt at the time. When these particles were first identified and named, the majority of other known elementary particles possessed significantly lower masses than the baryons. It was a simpler time, before the full menagerie of subatomic oddities was cataloged. Every baryon, much like a shadow following its form, possesses a corresponding [antiparticle](/Antiparticle), known as an antibaryon. In these antimatter counterparts, the constituent [quarks](/Quark) are precisely replaced by their corresponding antiquarks. Consider the [proton](/Proton), for example: it's a tripartite entity composed of two [up quarks](/Up_quark) and one [down quark](/Down_quark). Its mirror image, the [antiproton](/Antiproton), logically consists of two up antiquarks and one down antiquark. Symmetry, even in annihilation, has a certain elegance.

Baryons are not solitary entities; they are deeply entangled in the [residual strong force](/Residual_strong_force), a powerful interaction that is effectively [mediated](/Force_carrier) by other composite particles known as [mesons](/Meson). The most familiar and, frankly, vital baryons are the [protons](/Proton) and [neutrons](/Neutron). These triquark formations are the bedrock of the [universe](/Universe) as we know it, making up the overwhelming majority of the mass of all visible [matter](/Matter). They coalesce to form the very [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) of every [atom](/Atom) – a fact so fundamental it’s often overlooked. (It’s worth noting, of course, that [electrons](/Electron), those other crucial atomic components, belong to an entirely different lineage of particles called [leptons](/Lepton), and crucially, they do not participate in the strong force, preferring a less demanding existence.) Beyond these conventional triquarks, the universe, in its infinite capacity for surprise, has also unveiled [exotic baryons](/Exotic_baryon). These peculiar constructs, containing five [quarks](/Quark) – four quarks and one antiquark – are aptly named [pentaquarks](/Pentaquark), and their existence has been a fascinating, if initially controversial, subject of study.

Observational astronomy and cosmology, ever keen to take a census of the cosmos, indicate that the distribution of baryons across the [universe](/Universe) is somewhat disparate. A mere 10% of these fundamental building blocks are found nestled within galaxies, the luminous islands we so readily observe. A more substantial portion, estimated at 50 to 60%, resides in the vast, diffuse expanse of the [circumgalactic medium](/Circumgalactic_medium). The remaining 30 to 40% are thought to be scattered throughout the expansive, tenuous tendrils of the [warm–hot intergalactic medium](/Warm%E2%80%93hot_intergalactic_medium) (WHIM), a cosmic web that's as difficult to pinpoint as a coherent thought before coffee.

## Background

Baryons, as previously established, are fundamentally [strongly interacting](/Strong_interaction) [fermions](/Fermion). This means they are not merely influenced by the formidable [strong nuclear force](/Strong_nuclear_force) but are also governed by [Fermi–Dirac statistics](/Fermi%E2%80%93Dirac_statistics), a set of rules that dictate the behavior of all particles that obey the aforementioned [Pauli exclusion principle](/Pauli_exclusion_principle)—the cosmic decree that no two identical fermions can occupy the same quantum state simultaneously. This behavior stands in stark contrast to [bosons](/Boson), which, with their lack of adherence to the exclusion principle, are far more gregarious.

Alongside [mesons](/Meson) (which consist of a quark-antiquark pair), baryons collectively form the class of [hadrons](/Hadron)—composite particles that are, at their core, made of [quarks](/Quark). The concept of [baryon number](/Baryon_number) (B) is crucial here: individual quarks are assigned a baryon number of B = 1/3, while their antimatter counterparts, antiquarks, carry a baryon number of B = −1/3. Thus, the term "baryon" most commonly refers to the archetypal triquarks—those baryons composed of three quarks, resulting in a total baryon number of B = (1/3) + (1/3) + (1/3) = 1. Simple arithmetic, yet profoundly significant.

However, the universe, as it often does, refuses to be entirely predictable. The existence of other, more [exotic baryons](/Exotic_baryon) has been theorized and, in some cases, tentatively observed. Among these hypothetical oddities are [pentaquarks](/Pentaquark), which would be baryons composed of four quarks and a single antiquark. This composition would still result in a baryon number of B = (1/3) + (1/3) + (1/3) + (1/3) − (1/3) = 1. For a considerable period, the particle physics community maintained a healthy skepticism regarding their existence, with evidence in 2006 largely viewed as inconclusive, and by 2008, widely considered to be overwhelmingly against the reported pentaquarks. However, as is often the case with groundbreaking discoveries, persistence pays off. In a dramatic turn of events in July 2015, the [LHCb](/LHCb) experiment at [CERN](/CERN) announced the observation of two distinct resonances. These signals were remarkably consistent with pentaquark states, detected within the decay products of a Λ<sup>0</sup><sub>b</sub> → J/ψK<sup>−</sup>p process, and boasted an almost impossibly high combined [statistical significance](/Statistical_significance) of 15σ. This observation effectively brought pentaquarks from the realm of theoretical speculation into the tangible world of experimental physics, reminding us that nature often holds more complexity than our models initially suggest.

The theoretical landscape doesn't stop at five quarks. In principle, one could imagine even more complex structures, such as heptaquarks (comprising five quarks and two antiquarks) or nonaquarks (six quarks and three antiquarks), each still maintaining a net baryon number of 1. Whether these highly exotic configurations will ever materialize in accelerator experiments or remain purely mathematical curiosities is, as yet, an open question, and one that frankly, might not keep me up at night.

## Baryonic matter

Almost all the [matter](/Matter) that you, in your limited daily existence, encounter or interact with—the chair you sit on, the air you breathe, the very body you inhabit—is classified as [baryonic matter](/Matter). This classification encompasses [atoms](/Atom) of every conceivable sort, and it is precisely these baryons that bestow upon them the fundamental property of mass. Conversely, [non-baryonic matter](/Dark_matter), as its name rather plainly implies, is any form of matter not predominantly composed of baryons. This vast and mysterious category includes the elusive [neutrinos](/Neutrino) and free [electrons](/Electron), the enigmatic components of [dark matter](/Dark_matter) (which, despite its name, is not necessarily "matter" in the conventional sense), various [supersymmetric particles](/Supersymmetry) if they exist, hypothetical entities like [axions](/Axion), and even the gravitational singularities known as [black holes](/Black_hole). The universe, it seems, is far more diverse in its fundamental constituents than our everyday experience suggests.

The mere existence of baryons, particularly their current abundance, presents a profound and enduring puzzle in the field of [cosmology](/Cosmology). According to the prevailing [Big Bang](/Big_Bang) model, the very early universe should have produced an almost perfectly equal quantity of baryons and antibaryons. Yet, here we are, in a universe utterly dominated by matter, with antimatter being a rare and fleeting phenomenon. The intricate, and still not fully understood, process by which baryons came to vastly outnumber their [antiparticles](/Antiparticle) is known as [baryogenesis](/Baryogenesis). It is, to put it mildly, a significant cosmic asymmetry that demands explanation.

## Baryogenesis

The question of why there is more matter than antimatter—and thus, why we exist at all—is a central enigma in modern cosmology, addressed by the theory of [baryogenesis](/Baryogenesis). Current experimental observations are remarkably consistent with the principle that the total number of [quarks](/Quark) in the [universe](/Universe) is conserved, a conservation law that extends to the overall [baryon number](/Baryon_number), with [antibaryons](/Antiparticle) conventionally assigned negative quantities. Within the framework of the prevailing [Standard Model](/Standard_Model) of [particle physics](/Particle_physics), the number of baryons *can* theoretically change, but only in multiples of three, a process mediated by hypothetical particles known as [sphalerons](/Sphaleron). However, such events are exceedingly rare and, crucially, have never been directly observed in any experiment to date.

Looking beyond the [Standard Model](/Standard_Model), some speculative but compelling [Grand Unified Theories](/Grand_Unified_Theory) (GUTs) of [particle physics](/Particle_physics) propose that a single [proton](/Proton) could, in principle, undergo a process of [proton decay](/Proton_decay), thereby changing the baryon number by one unit. This would provide a mechanism for baryogenesis, as it implies a fundamental asymmetry in the universe's early moments. However, despite concerted efforts and sophisticated detectors designed to observe such an event, [proton decay](/Proton_decay) remains stubbornly unobserved. The current, widely accepted explanation for the observed excess of baryons over [antibaryons](/Antiparticle) in our present [universe](/Universe) hinges on the notion of non-[conservation of baryon number](/Conservation_of_baryon_number) occurring during the extremely early stages of cosmic evolution. While this theoretical framework provides a plausible avenue, the precise mechanisms and conditions under which this imbalance arose are still far from being thoroughly understood, leaving a gaping void in our otherwise elegant cosmic narrative.

## Properties

### Isospin and charge

The concept of [isospin](/Isospin) is one of those historical artifacts in [particle physics](/Particle_physics) that, while not entirely accurate in its initial interpretation, proved remarkably useful and remains a classification tool today. It was first conceived by the brilliant [Werner Heisenberg](/Werner_Heisenberg) in 1932. His goal was to account for the striking similarities observed between [protons](/Proton) and [neutrons](/Neutron) when they interacted via the [strong interaction](/Strong_interaction). Despite possessing distinctly different [electric charges](/Electric_charge) (the proton being positive, the neutron neutral), their masses were so uncannily similar that physicists, quite reasonably, began to suspect they were merely different manifestations of the *same* fundamental particle. The observed differences in electric charge were then hypothesized to be the result of some as-yet-unknown internal excitation, a quantum property analogous to [spin](/Spin_(physics)). This enigmatic internal degree of freedom was later, in 1937, christened "isospin" by [Eugene Wigner](/Eugene_Wigner).

This rather elegant, if ultimately incomplete, belief system persisted until the watershed moment of 1964, when [Murray Gell-Mann](/Murray_Gell-Mann) (and independently, [George Zweig](/George_Zweig)) proposed the revolutionary [quark model](/Quark_model). This model, in its initial formulation, posited the existence of just three fundamental [quarks](/Quark): the [up](/Up_quark) (u), [down](/Down_quark) (d), and [strange](/Strange_quark) (s) quarks. The profound success of the earlier [isospin](/Isospin) model is now understood to be a direct consequence of the very similar masses shared by the [up](/Up_quark) and [down quarks](/Down_quark). Because these two quarks are almost indistinguishable in mass, any composite particles (like baryons) formed from them in similar numbers will naturally exhibit similar overall masses. The precise [electric charge](/Electric_charge) of such a particle is then simply determined by its specific complement of [up](/Up_quark) and [down quarks](/Down_quark), as [up quarks](/Up_quark) carry a charge of +2/3 *e* (where *e* is the elementary charge) while [down quarks](/Down_quark) carry a charge of −1/3 *e*.

Take, for example, the four members of the [Delta baryon](/Delta_baryon) family. They all possess different charges: the Δ<sup>++</sup> (composed of uuu), Δ<sup>+</sup> (uud), Δ<sup>0</sup> (udd), and Δ<sup>−</sup> (ddd). Yet, despite these charge disparities, they exhibit remarkably similar masses, clustering around ~1,232 [MeV/c<sup>2](/Electronvolt)</sup>. This is because each is fundamentally constructed from a combination of three [up](/Up_quark) or [down quarks](/Down_quark). Under the older [isospin](/Isospin) model, these four distinct entities were erroneously considered to be merely different charged states of a single, underlying "Delta particle."

The mathematical framework for [isospin](/Isospin) was deliberately constructed to parallel that of [spin](/Spin_(physics)). [Isospin](/Isospin) projections, much like [spin](/Spin_(physics)) projections, vary in integer increments of 1. Each such projection was then associated with a specific "[charged state](/Quantum_state)." Since the "Delta particle" was observed to have four such "charged states," it was assigned an [isospin](/Isospin) value of I = 3/2. Its individual "charged states"—Δ<sup>++</sup>, Δ<sup>+</sup>, Δ<sup>0</sup>, and Δ<sup>−</sup>—were then mapped to the [isospin](/Isospin) projections I<sub>3</sub> = +3/2, I<sub>3</sub> = +1/2, I<sub>3</sub> = −1/2, and I<sub>3</sub> = −3/2, respectively. Another classic illustration is the "nucleon particle." With its two observed "charged states"—the positive nucleon N<sup>+</sup> (the [proton](/Proton)) and the neutral nucleon N<sup>0</sup> (the [neutron](/Neutron))—it was assigned an [isospin](/Isospin) of I = 1/2. The [proton](/Proton) was identified with I<sub>3</sub> = +1/2, and the [neutron](/Neutron) with I<sub>3</sub> = −1/2. Later, a more precise relationship between the [isospin](/Isospin) projections and the actual [up](/Up_quark) and [down quark](/Down_quark) content of particles was established through the following formula:

$I_{\mathrm {3} }={\frac {1}{2}}[(n_{\mathrm {u} }-n_{\mathrm {\bar {u}} })-(n_{\mathrm {d} }-n_{\mathrm {\bar {d}} })],$

where *n*<sub>u</sub> and *n*<sub>d</sub> represent the number of [up](/Up_quark) and [down quarks](/Down_quark), respectively, and *n*<sub>ū</sub> and *n*<sub>đ</sub> denote the number of [up](/Up_quark) and [down antiquarks](/Down_quark).

In the anachronistic "isospin picture," the four [Deltas](/Delta_baryon) and the two [nucleons](/Nucleon) were viewed as mere different states of only two underlying particles. However, the more accurate [quark model](/Quark_model) clarifies that the [Deltas](/Delta_baryon) are indeed distinct particles from the [nucleons](/Nucleon), with combinations like N<sup>++</sup> or N<sup>−</sup> being fundamentally forbidden by the [Pauli exclusion principle](/Pauli%27s_exclusion_principle) for nucleons in their ground state. While [isospin](/Isospin), in its original formulation, presented an admittedly inaccurate depiction of the underlying reality, it remains a surprisingly effective and entrenched tool for classifying baryons, albeit one that occasionally leads to rather unnatural and often bewildering nomenclature for those attempting to navigate the labyrinthine world of [particle physics](/Particle_physics).

### Flavour quantum numbers

Beyond [isospin](/Isospin), other [flavour quantum numbers](/Flavour_(particle_physics)) were introduced to categorize the growing menagerie of particles. The [strangeness](/Strangeness) (S) [flavour quantum number](/Flavour_(particle_physics))—not to be conflated with [spin](/Spin_(physics))—was one of the first to be noticed, exhibiting a curious inverse correlation with particle mass: the greater the mass of a particle within a given multiplet, the lower its [strangeness](/Strangeness) (meaning, generally, the more [strange quarks](/Strange_quark) it contained). This allowed for a more comprehensive description of particles, mapping them according to their [isospin](/Isospin) projections (which, as we know, are linked to [charge](/Electric_charge)) and their [strangeness](/Strangeness) (which correlates with mass). Visual representations like the [uds octet](/Eightfold_way_(physics)) and [decuplet](/Eightfold_way_(physics)) figures elegantly illustrate this classification.

As more [quarks](/Quark) were discovered beyond the initial [up](/Up_quark), [down](/Down_quark), and [strange](/Strange_quark)—specifically the [charm](/Charm_quark) (c), [bottom](/Bottom_quark) (b), and [top](/Top_quark) (t) quarks—new [quantum numbers](/Quantum_numbers) were systematically introduced to extend this descriptive framework to include udc and udb octets and decuplets. However, it quickly became apparent that this elegant system, which so neatly linked particle mass and charge to [isospin](/Isospin) and [flavour quantum numbers](/Flavour_(particle_physics)), worked best for multiplets constructed from one [up](/Up_quark), one [down](/Down_quark), and *one other* quark. The reason for this selective success lies in the disparate masses of the quarks. Only the [up](/Up_quark) and [down quarks](/Down_quark) possess sufficiently similar masses to allow for the kind of symmetry that underpins the [isospin](/Isospin) concept. When other, much heavier quarks are involved, this descriptive power begins to falter, and the system breaks down for other potential octets and decuplets (e.g., a ucb octet or decuplet would not exhibit the same clear patterns).

If all [quarks](/Quark) were to possess identical masses, their behavior would be described as perfectly [symmetric](/Broken_symmetry); they would all interact with the [strong interaction](/Strong_interaction) in precisely the same manner. However, since quarks do *not* have identical masses (a fundamental truth of the [Standard Model](/Standard_Model)), their interactions are not perfectly symmetrical. Just as an electron accelerates more dramatically than a proton in the same electric field due to its lighter mass, so too do quarks of different masses respond differently to the [strong force](/Strong_interaction). This deviation from perfect symmetry is formally referred to as [broken symmetry](/Broken_symmetry).

The relationship between [charge](/Electric_charge) (*Q*), [isospin](/Isospin) projection (*I*<sub>3</sub>), [baryon number](/Baryon_number) (*B*), and the various [flavour quantum numbers](/Flavour_(particle_physics)) (*S*, *C*, *B′*, *T*) was elegantly codified by the [Gell-Mann–Nishijima formula](/Gell-Mann%E2%80%93Nishijima_formula):

$Q=I_{3}+{\frac {1}{2}}\left(B+S+C+B^{\prime }+T\right),$

where *S* represents [strangeness](/Strangeness), *C* denotes [charm](/Charm_(quantum_number)), *B′* indicates [bottomness](/Bottomness), and *T* stands for [topness](/Topness). These [flavour quantum numbers](/Flavour_(particle_physics)) are themselves directly related to the net count of specific [quarks](/Quark) and [antiquarks](/Antiparticle) within a particle:

${\begin{aligned}S&=-\left(n_{\mathrm {s} }-n_{\mathrm {\bar {s}} }\right),\\C&=+\left(n_{\mathrm {c} }-n_{\mathrm {\bar {c}} }\right),\\B^{\prime }&=-\left(n_{\mathrm {b} }-n_{\mathrm {\bar {b}} }\right),\\T&=+\left(n_{\mathrm {t} }-n_{\mathrm {\bar {t}} }\right),\end{aligned}}$

Here, *n*<sub>s</sub>, *n*<sub>c</sub>, *n*<sub>b</sub>, and *n*<sub>t</sub> are the numbers of [strange](/Strange_quark), [charm](/Charm_quark), [bottom](/Bottom_quark), and [top quarks](/Top_quark), respectively, while *n*<sub>s̄</sub>, *n*<sub>c̄</sub>, *n*<sub>b̄</sub>, and *n*<sub>t̄</sub> denote their corresponding [antiquarks](/Antiparticle).

Crucially, this means that the [Gell-Mann–Nishijima formula](/Gell-Mann%E2%80%93Nishijima_formula) can be equivalently expressed directly in terms of a particle's underlying [quark](/Quark) content, offering a more fundamental perspective on its [charge](/Electric_charge):

$Q={\frac {2}{3}}\left[(n_{\mathrm {u} }-n_{\mathrm {\bar {u}} })+(n_{\mathrm {c} }-n_{\mathrm {\bar {c}} })+(n_{\mathrm {t} }-n_{\mathrm {\bar {t}} })\right]-{\frac {1}{3}}\left[(n_{\mathrm {d} }-n_{\mathrm {\bar {d}} })+(n_{\mathrm {s}} -n_{\mathrm {\bar {s}} })+(n_{\mathrm {b}} -n_{\mathrm {\bar {b}} })\right].$

This equation elegantly demonstrates how the fractional [charges](/Electric_charge) of the individual [quarks](/Quark) (either +2/3 *e* for [up](/Up_quark)-type quarks or −1/3 *e* for [down](/Down_quark)-type quarks) combine to yield the total integer or zero [charge](/Electric_charge) observed for composite particles like baryons. It's a testament to the predictive power of the [quark model](/Quark_model), even if the journey to this understanding involved some rather circuitous historical detours.

### Spin, orbital angular momentum, and total angular momentum

In the peculiar world of quantum mechanics, [spin](/Spin_(physics)) (represented by the [quantum number](/Quantum_numbers) *S*) is not a classical rotation, but rather an intrinsic, fundamental property of a particle—a [vector](/Euclidean_vector) quantity that acts as its "internal" [angular momentum](/Angular_momentum). It manifests in discrete increments of 1/2 [ħ](/Planck_constant), where ħ (pronounced "h-bar") is the reduced [Planck constant](/Planck_constant). This ħ is often omitted in discussions, implicitly understood as the "fundamental" unit of [spin](/Spin_(physics)), so when physicists speak of "spin 1," they are referring to "spin 1 ħ." In certain systems of [natural units](/Natural_units), ħ is even set to 1, making its explicit mention redundant.

All [quarks](/Quark) are [fermionic](/Fermion) particles and inherently possess a [spin](/Spin_(physics)) of 1/2 (S = 1/2). Because [spin](/Spin_(physics)) projections (the measured component of spin along a chosen axis) vary in increments of 1 ħ, a single quark has a [spin vector](/Spin_(physics)) of magnitude 1/2 and can exhibit two distinct spin projections: S<sub>z</sub> = +1/2 and S<sub>z</sub> = −1/2. When two [quarks](/Quark) combine, their spins can either align or anti-align. If their spins align, the two [spin vectors](/Spin_(physics)) add constructively to form a composite vector of total spin S = 1, which then has three possible spin projections: S<sub>z</sub> = +1, S<sub>z</sub> = 0, and S<sub>z</sub> = −1. Conversely, if the two quarks' spins are anti-aligned, their [spin vectors](/Spin_(physics)) cancel out, resulting in a total spin S = 0, with only a single projection: S<sub>z</sub> = 0.

Since baryons are, by definition, constructed from *three* [quarks](/Quark), their individual [spin vectors](/Spin_(physics)) can combine in more complex ways. The collective [spin](/Spin_(physics)) of a baryon can either sum to a total spin S = 3/2, which yields four possible spin projections (S<sub>z</sub> = +3/2, S<sub>z</sub> = +1/2, S<sub>z</sub> = −1/2, and S<sub>z</sub> = −3/2), or to a total spin S = 1/2, which results in two spin projections (S<sub>z</sub> = +1/2 and S<sub>z</sub> = −1/2). This intrinsic spin is just one component of a particle's complete angular momentum profile.

There exists another crucial form of [angular momentum](/Angular_momentum), distinct from [spin](/Spin_(physics)), known as [orbital angular momentum](/Angular_momentum_operator). This quantity, represented by the [azimuthal quantum number](/Azimuthal_quantum_number) *L*, also comes in discrete increments of 1 ħ. It accounts for the [angular momentum](/Angular_momentum) generated by the constituent [quarks](/Quark) orbiting around each other within the baryon, much like planets orbiting a star, albeit in a quantum mechanical sense. The [total angular momentum](/Angular_momentum_operator) (*J*) of a particle is therefore a composite quantity, combining both its intrinsic [angular momentum](/Angular_momentum) ([spin](/Spin_(physics))) and its [orbital angular momentum](/Angular_momentum_operator). The possible values for *J* are determined by the vector addition of *L* and *S*, ranging from J = |L − S| to J = |L + S|, also in increments of 1.

| Spin, S | Orbital angular momentum, L | Total angular momentum, J | Parity, P | Condensed notation, J<sup>P</sup> |
| :------ | :-------------------------- | :------------------------ | :-------- | :------------------------------ |
| 1/2     | 0                           | 1/2                       | +         | 1/2<sup>+</sup>                 |
|         | 1                           | 3/2, 1/2                  | −         | 3/2<sup>−</sup>, 1/2<sup>−</sup>      |
|         | 2                           | 5/2, 3/2                  | +         | 5/2<sup>+</sup>, 3/2<sup>+</sup>      |
|         | 3                           | 7/2, 5/2                  | −         | 7/2<sup>−</sup>, 5/2<sup>−</sup>      |
| 3/2     | 0                           | 3/2                       | +         | 3/2<sup>+</sup>                 |
|         | 1                           | 5/2, 3/2, 1/2             | −         | 5/2<sup>−</sup>, 3/2<sup>−</sup>, 1/2<sup>−</sup> |
|         | 2                           | 7/2, 5/2, 3/2, 1/2        | +         | 7/2<sup>+</sup>, 5/2<sup>+</sup>, 3/2<sup>+</sup>, 1/2<sup>+</sup> |
|         | 3                           | 9/2, 7/2, 5/2, 3/2        | −         | 9/2<sup>−</sup>, 7/2<sup>−</sup>, 5/2<sup>−</sup>, 3/2<sup>−</sup> |

[Particle physicists](/Particle_physics) are often particularly interested in baryons that possess no [orbital angular momentum](/Angular_momentum_operator) (L = 0), as these configurations typically correspond to the [ground states](/Ground_state)—the lowest possible energy states—of the particles. Consequently, the two primary groups of baryons that have been most extensively investigated are those with S = 1/2; L = 0 and S = 3/2; L = 0. These configurations directly lead to total [angular momentum quantum numbers](/Total_angular_momentum_quantum_number) of J = 1/2<sup>+</sup> and J = 3/2<sup>+</sup>, respectively (the superscript denotes [parity](/Parity_(physics)), which we'll get to). It is crucial to remember, however, that these are by no means the *only* possible configurations. For instance, a baryon with J = 3/2<sup>+</sup> can also arise from a combination of S = 1/2 and L = 2, or even from S = 3/2 and L = 2. This intriguing phenomenon, where multiple distinct quantum states can yield the same total [angular momentum](/Angular_momentum) value, is referred to as [degeneracy](/Degenerate_energy_level). Disentangling and distinguishing between these degenerate baryons represents an active and challenging frontier in the field of [baryon spectroscopy](/Baryon_spectroscopy), where researchers meticulously probe the internal structure of these composite particles. It's a bit like trying to identify different types of fruit from their shadows alone; sometimes, the simplest explanation isn't the complete one.

### Parity

Imagine, if you will, the entire [universe](/Universe) being perfectly reflected in a mirror. For the most part, the fundamental laws of [physics](/Physics) would remain entirely unchanged; phenomena would unfold identically, regardless of whether we arbitrarily label one side "left" and the other "right." This profound concept of mirror reflection symmetry is formally known as "[intrinsic parity](/Parity_(physics))" or, more simply, "parity" (*P*). The fundamental forces of [gravity](/Gravity), the [electromagnetic force](/Electromagnetic_force), and the immensely powerful [strong interaction](/Strong_interaction) all exhibit this perfect symmetry; their operations are indifferent to whether the universe is mirrored or not, and thus they are said to [conserve parity](/P-symmetry) (P-symmetry). However, the [weak interaction](/Weak_interaction), that subtle orchestrator of nuclear decay, is a notable exception. It demonstrably *does* distinguish between "left" and "right," a profound asymmetry known as [parity violation](/Parity_violation) (P-violation), first observed in the 1950s.

Building upon this, if the [wavefunction](/Wavefunction) for every individual particle (or, more precisely, the [quantum field](/Quantum_field) describing each particle type) were to be simultaneously mirror-reversed, one might intuitively expect the resulting set of wavefunctions to perfectly satisfy the laws of [physics](/Physics) (with the obvious caveat of the [weak interaction](/Weak_interaction)). Yet, the universe, in its subtle complexity, offers a twist: for the equations to truly hold, the wavefunctions of certain particle types must also be multiplied by an additional factor of −1, in conjunction with being mirror-reversed. Such particles are then designated as having negative or odd [parity](/Parity_(physics)) (*P* = −1, or simply P = –). Conversely, particles whose wavefunctions do not require this additional sign flip are said to possess positive or even [parity](/Parity_(physics)) (*P* = +1, or P = +).

For baryons, this intrinsic [parity](/Parity_(physics)) is elegantly linked to their [orbital angular momentum](/Angular_momentum_operator) (*L*) by a straightforward relation:

$P=(-1)^{L}.$

As a direct consequence of this formula, any baryon that exists in a state with no [orbital angular momentum](/Angular_momentum_operator) (L = 0)—that is to say, its constituent [quarks](/Quark) are not orbiting each other—will invariably possess even [parity](/Parity_(physics)) (*P* = +1). This connection between internal dynamics and a fundamental symmetry property underscores the intricate quantum ballet performed within these composite particles.

## Nomenclature

The classification of baryons into distinct groups is a rigorous process, primarily based on their [isospin](/Isospin) (*I*) values and their fundamental [quark](/Quark) (q) composition. The established taxonomy recognizes six primary groups of baryons: the [nucleon](/Nucleon) (N), [Delta](/Delta_baryon) (Δ), [Lambda](/Lambda_baryon) (Λ), [Sigma](/Sigma_baryon) (Σ), [Xi](/Xi_baryon) (Ξ), and [Omega](/Omega_baryon) (Ω). These systematic rules for classification are meticulously defined and maintained by the [Particle Data Group](/Particle_Data_Group), the authoritative body for particle physics information. A key distinction in these rules is the categorization of [up](/Up_quark) (u), [down](/Down_quark) (d), and [strange](/Strange_quark) (s) quarks as "light" and the [charm](/Charm_quark) (c), [bottom](/Bottom_quark) (b), and [top](/Top_quark) (t) quarks as "heavy." These guidelines are comprehensive, theoretically covering all possible baryons that could be formed from any combination of three out of the six known [quark flavours](/Flavour_(particle_physics)), even extending to hypothetical baryons containing [top quarks](/Top_quark), despite the fact that such particles are not expected to exist in nature due to the extraordinarily short lifetime of the [top quark](/Top_quark). It is important to note, however, that these established rules do *not* encompass the classification of [pentaquarks](/Pentaquark), which, as we've seen, represent a more recently confirmed and exotic form of baryonic matter.

Let's delve into the specific classification rules:

*   **[Nucleon](/Nucleon) (N) and [Delta](/Delta_baryon) (Δ) Baryons**: Any baryon composed exclusively of (any combination of) three [up](/Up_quark) and/or [down quarks](/Down_quark) falls into one of these two categories. If the baryon has an [isospin](/Isospin) of I = 1/2, it is classified as a [nucleon](/Nucleon) (e.g., [proton](/Proton), [neutron](/Neutron)). If its [isospin](/Isospin) is I = 3/2, it is a [Delta baryon](/Delta_baryon).
*   **[Lambda](/Lambda_baryon) (Λ) and [Sigma](/Sigma_baryon) (Σ) Baryons**: These baryons contain exactly two [up](/Up_quark) and/or [down quarks](/Down_quark), with the third quark being a heavier [flavour](/Flavour_(particle_physics)). If the [isospin](/Isospin) is I = 0, it's a [Lambda baryon](/Lambda_baryon). If I = 1, it's a [Sigma baryon](/Sigma_baryon). The identity of the heavier third quark is explicitly indicated by a subscript (e.g., Λ<sub>c</sub> contains a [charm quark](/Charm_quark)).
*   **[Xi](/Xi_baryon) (Ξ) Baryons**: Baryons in this group contain only one [up](/Up_quark) or [down quark](/Down_quark), with the remaining two quarks being heavier [flavours](/Flavour_(particle_physics)). They are characterized by an [isospin](/Isospin) of I = 1/2. One or two subscripts are appended to the symbol to specify the identities of these heavier quarks (e.g., Ξ<sub>cc</sub> contains two [charm quarks](/Charm_quark)).
*   **[Omega](/Omega_baryon) (Ω) Baryons**: This class is reserved for baryons that contain *no* [up](/Up_quark) or [down quarks](/Down_quark) at all; they are composed entirely of three heavier [flavours](/Flavour_(particle_physics)). [Omega baryons](/Omega_baryon) have an [isospin](/Isospin) of I = 0. Subscripts are used to denote the specific heavy [quark](/Quark) content (e.g., Ω<sub>b</sub> contains two [strange quarks](/Strange_quark) and one [bottom quark](/Bottom_quark)).
*   **Mass Notation**: For baryons that undergo strong decays (i.e., they have very short lifetimes and decay rapidly via the [strong interaction](/Strong_interaction)), their measured masses are incorporated directly into their names. A prime example is the Δ<sup>++</sup>(1232), where "1232" indicates its approximate mass in [MeV/c<sup>2](/Electronvolt)</sup>. In contrast, particles like Σ<sup>0</sup>, which do not decay strongly, do not include their mass in their primary designation.

Beyond these fundamental rules, a widespread (though, regrettably, not entirely universal) practice involves additional conventions for distinguishing between certain states that might otherwise share the same symbolic representation. Such inconsistencies are, of course, a minor irritation in any classification system.

*   **Asterisk Notation**: Baryons with a [total angular momentum](/Total_angular_momentum) of J = 3/2 that happen to share the same basic symbol as their J = 1/2 counterparts are typically denoted by an asterisk (e.g., Σ*). This conveniently differentiates their spin states.
*   **Prime Notation**: When two distinct baryons can be formed from three different [quark](/Quark) [flavours](/Flavour_(particle_physics)) and both exist in a J = 1/2 configuration, a prime symbol (′) is used to differentiate between them.
*   **The Λ/Σ Exception**: There's a particular exception to the prime notation. When two of the three constituent [quarks](/Quark) are specifically an [up](/Up_quark) and a [down quark](/Down_quark) (and the third is heavier), one of the resulting baryons is uniquely designated as a [Lambda](/Lambda_baryon) (Λ), while the other is designated as a [Sigma](/Sigma_baryon) (Σ). This historical quirk in nomenclature persists.

Ultimately, the [charge](/Electric_charge) of a particle serves as an invaluable, indirect clue to its underlying [quark](/Quark) composition. For instance, if you encounter a Λ<sup>+</sup><sub>c</sub>, the classification rules inform us that it contains a [charm quark](/Charm_quark) (c) and some combination of two [up](/Up_quark) and/or [down quarks](/Down_quark). Since a [charm quark](/Charm_quark) carries a charge of +2/3 *e*, for the total charge of the Λ<sup>+</sup><sub>c</sub> to be +1 *e*, the remaining two quarks must necessarily be an [up quark](/Up_quark) (+2/3 *e*) and a [down quark](/Down_quark) (−1/3 *e*). This simple deduction reveals the full quark content (u d c) and highlights the elegant, if occasionally convoluted, internal logic of particle nomenclature.

